                "text": "I don’t have enough information in the Lattes data provided to determine which single 2024 item is **“most relevant”** (there’s no ranking metric such as journal quartile, impact factor, citation count, awards for the paper, etc.).\n\nHowever, in **2024** this researcher has the following **bibliographic production** recorded in the Lattes entries (journal articles + one conference proceedings paper):\n\n### Journal articles (2024)\n- **“IFORS' Operational Research Hall of Fame: Clóvis Caesar Gonzaga”** — *International Transactions in Operational Research* (vol. 31, pp. 2796–2798). DOI: 10.1111/itor.13432  \n- **“On the total chromatic number of the direct product of cycles and complete graphs”** — *RAIRO-Operations Research* (vol. 58, pp. 1609–1632). DOI: 10.1051/ro/2024045  \n- **“The hardness of recognising poorly matchable graphs and the hunting of the d-snark”** — *RAIRO-Operations Research* (vol. 58, pp. 2055–2073). DOI: 10.1051/ro/2024068  \n- **“Parameterized algorithms for Steiner tree and (connected) dominating set on path graphs”** — *Networks* (vol. 84, pp. 132–147). DOI: 10.1002/net.22220  \n- **“Canonical cuts of path powers”** — *Contributions to Discrete Mathematics* (vol. 19, pp. 121–136). DOI: 10.55016/ojs/cdm.v19i3.72392  \n\n### Conference proceedings (2024)\n- **“Pebbling in Kneser Graphs”** — in *Latin American Symposium on Theoretical Informatics, 2024* (vol. 14579, pp. 46–60). DOI: 10.1007/978-3-031-55601-2_4  \n\nIf you tell me what criterion you mean by **“most relevant”** (e.g., “highest-impact journal”, “journal over conference”, “most cited”, or “first/last author”), I can narrow it down using only the information available here.",
